Mimicked, you aren't shit. Stop saying you are. I used to do the same with my writing, so I kinda know the headspace you're probably in. The self-doubt and confidence issues aren't gonna go away by just telling yourself, "hey, I think I suck at [thing], so anyone who thinks I'm good at it must be wrong." Trust me, I know it doesn't leave. I dealt with it. It took me a long time to finally come to terms with myself as a person and as a writer. What really hit me was when I realized people saw things in my work that I couldn't. They got something out of it I never did, and that meant something. Something really profound. I mean, if these people can find joy and entertainment out of the thing I think I'm shit at, then surely I can't be as shit as I thought, right? There has to be something there for people to get something out if it.
It's the same with art. You may see the flaws and the issues and may not even agree that it's well done, but stop looking at the negatives. Look at the positives. Everyone else already does, after all. They want to see nice art and stories, and they love to see a writefag or artfag produce things for this general. We're a niche group with niche kinks, so we gotta help each other out every now and then, which is why I'm even doing this.
